{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_chucktaylor_ver02/data/sn86058242/00271745977/1913060301/0320.xml":{"full_text":"LAKE COUMTY TIME\nMOSTLY CLOUDY\nTODAY; PROBABLY\nSHOWERS; WARMER.\nLJl\nEDITION\nVOL. VII., NO. 296.\nHAMMOND, INDIANA, TUESDAY, JUNE 3,1913.\nONE CENT PER COPY.\n.(Back Numbers t Cents Copy.)\nPtJRT.\nB hi TIFT\nT\nSLVEMMG\nELLE\nMILE\nDM\nSTORYWA\nWHOLLY A\nFABRIGAT\nPETERSON\nFIDS THAT\nPost Yarn About Munster\nFranchises Without Jot of\nTruth; Hustling. Town\nHad Granted Franchises a\nMonth Ago.\nReliable news was apparently scarce\nIn the office of the Gary Post last Sat\nurday, Judging from a ridiculous col\numn article on the front page in which\ntwo tears were shed one for the Gary\nSouthern lnterurban because it did\nnot get a franchise in Munster, 'and\nthe other for the people of Munster be\ncause (boo-hoo) the poor Munster peo\nple may not get an lnterurban at all\nnow. Gary people of course knew the\nstory was not true because The Times\nprinted the story of the franchise\ngranting long ago.\nRoth Have FraicUwi.\nThe fact of the matter is, both the\nGary Southern and tlte Green line,\nthe latter operating between the North\ntownship cities and Chicago, have\nfranchises in Munster. The franchises\nwere granted a day or two before the\npublic utilities law went into effect on\nMay 1, and each company has a. year\nin which to begin operations, or lose\nits franchise rights.\nAlthough both companies have fran\nchises, only one company's tracks the\none building first shall occupy the\nRidge road In Munster. The other\ncompany then, if it desires to operate\nmust enter into an agreement with the\nfirst company. In Munster the Gary\nSouthern has a franchise as far west\nWashington, June 3. That the big\nbusiness interests of northern Indiana\nare flourishing in the face of tariff re\nvision downward. Is the contention of\nRepresentative Peterson, who has just\nreturned from visiting his district. Mr.\nPeterson, who succeeded Edgar D.\nCrumpacker as congressman from the\ndistrict that stands next to the Indi\nanapolis district in industrial Import\nance, made the first trip back home for\nthe sole purpose of getting first hand\ninformation regarding the attitude of\nmanufacturers and business men on\nthe business outlook.\nFinds Business Booming.\n\"I found business booming in my dis\ntrict,\" said the congressman. \"I talk\ned to a score of manufacturers and\nprofessional and business men about\n(Continued on Page J.\nM'CLAY\nHAS\nMANY\nCONTRACTS\nJ. H .McClay, the Hammond build\ning contractor, has $50,000 worth of\nbuildings under way in East Chicago\nand Indiana Harbor. The East Chi\ncago contract involves a two-story\nstore and flat building for Fred Mot\nof Hammond, while the Indiana Har\nbor work is for a new church and\nschool for St. Francis' Roman Catholic\ncongregation of which the Rev. J. Jak-\nsetys is the rector. The building is to\ncost $25,000 and is to be located at\n139th and Hemlock streets.\nThe Mott building in East Chicago\non Chicago avenue, just east of For\nsyth avenue, will be a decided Improve\nment for .the street. The structure\nwill cost approximately $25,000. It\nwill have two store rooms on the main\nfloor and four flats on the second floor.\nIt will be erected on a lot 50 by 90 feet\non the north side of the street.\nCrown Point Congressman o n His Retunfto Washington\nDeclares He Has Visite d Manufacturers by Score in\nThis District and They A ssured Him Prospects for a\nProsperous Year Were E xcellent.\nONE WILL BE KING OF ITALY SOME DAY;\nA PATH OF PRIMROSES FOR THE OTHER\nthe general business outlook and with\nout exception they assured me that the\noutlook for a prosperous year was\nbright. I made the rounds of the\nCalumet region In an automobile and\ntalked personally to the president of\nevery large manufacturing plant in\nHammond, Gary. East Chicago, Indiana\nHarbor and Whiting. Every one of\nthem told me that he was not a bit\nafraid that the new tariff bill would\nhurt his business.\nGood Outlook For Steel Men.\n\"The steel manufacturers at Gary\nare happy over the prospect of doing a\nrecord breaking business this year.\nSeveral of the smaller manufacturers,\nincluding one manufacturer at East\nChicago, who turns out Swedish Iron,\nare anxious that the Underwood bill be\n'Conti-d on Page 7.)\nTOLSTOI GETS\nTHIS MAN \"IN BAD'\nWhiskey Helps a Little and j\na Fine Follows. j\n'DEFIED DEATH IN\nRACE, KILLED LATER\nReading Tolstoi and drinking raw\nwhiskey at the same time Jacob HaiTy Martin, Slain in AutO\nKonke, 155th place, West Hammond, i\nworked himself into a sert of aesthet-\nWreck, Mechanician at\nSpeedway Races.\nic state of intoxication last night.\nHe made so much fuss about it that\nhis wife had him arrested. He was\nfined a dollar and cORts by Judge Adam\nStachowic in the West Hammond city 1\nAWi- I IT. r-.i\ncuun ims iiiurmng uf uu wio unioriunaie man\nThe book of Tolstoi was exhibit \"A.\" whose ttntimely end near Wolcott was\nit snowed up jacoo s temperament. uescriDea in tnese columns yesterday\nA black eye on one of the family was was a mechanician In the Stutx No. 2\nexhibit \"B.\" car ln tne Indianapolis speedway race\nand came out of that death grind with\nNo Clue to Loss. l1 l \"\"tln AT\" dvlnK to CWclso\njin a 6 cylinder Alco and took the wheel\njuttn AuaracnjK, lea uusiiin cireei, Lafayette\nHammond, is atill inniirnlnp the 1oa\nKi,i- A race was started between the Alco\n$400. which was either lost on a street f\" a.nd a Mercer roadster and the two\ncar or was taken out of his pocket by, \"at7nes Z taring along the\na sneakthief while he was on his wayuntry rd aa fa8t 8 thy could be\nhome Sunday afternoon. The money j frlven- The Mercer was a short dls\nwas his hard-earned savings with anc ahCad as the S\"turn ln the road\nwhich he was going to pay the last'9 8uth of Wolcott was reached,\npayment on his little home. The police nd e du8t from U mad Impossible\nwere notified and investigated the case, I for Mrt,n ee the second turn in the\nunm mo late to make the turn\nine car turned over in the ditch\nThere were no titers, not even a bid\nder for the Central \"school property,\nwhich was offered for sale by the board\nof education at 2 o'clock this afternoon.\nNo man or syndicate came forth to bid\n$175,000, the appraised value.\nWJien the court-house clock struck\ntwo. Superintendent C. M. McDaniel\nrapped on the concrete sidewalk ln\nfront of the building and announced\nthat the sale of the property would\nnow begin. Trustee John F. Krost very\nsolemnly read the official announce\nment, but there was not even an audi\nence.\nThe board bad proposed the sale to\nraise money for the new Industrial\ntraining high school. But two courses\nnow remain open for it if it wants to\nproceed. It can make another effort to\nsell the property on a lower appraise\nment, or it can proceed to issue bonds.\nThree hundred thousand dollars are\nneeded to carry out the industrial train\ning high school plans. The board has\n$75,000 on hand. By next fall it will\nbe in a position to-issue bonds for an\nadditional $125.0004 Thus with two\nthirds of the needed money the project\ncould be well put under way.\nHad the property been sold today,\nthe first step would have been to en\nlarge the Washington school. The\nboard feels that something must be\ndone to relieve the crowded condition\nin the Central school. If the Lincoln\nJefferson school property falls in the\nright hands the board hopes to rent\nthat building for temporary relief. It\nIs now studying the feasibility of port\nable schools.\nAlthough Attorney W. J. Whinery,\nacting for Contractors Caldwell &,flled\na petition for an injunction in the su-\nP AIJI'LDIIJUlllUMlJn.llftOWJI.ll.lllllgUJlKv ijjiS V y I\njt f :-JTt5c, -i h.. i.i,\nSwir\nGIF\nFinanciering Meth\nods of Traction\nSchemer Are\nRecalled\nUpon i the showing made by, the at\ntorneys for the defense, the state cas\nporter court, lt,4a rr.l.hSM,igbtlftat J4JBiMV)aL;,Du, IraS--MiUatone, lfeeQarx\nbut no clues have been found.\nSUBSCRIBK KCIK THE TIMES-\nJ ohn Younger HI.\nJohn Younger, 307 Sibley street, col\nlector for The Times Is still confined\nto his bed where he has been suffering\nfrom a number of carbuncles. Mr.\nYounger was very restless and in a\ngreat deal of pain last night, but today\nis reported showing some improvement.\nProviding no other complications set\nin it is thought that he will be able to\nbe up and round in a short time.\nand\nMartin was caught beneath the steer\ning wheel and his life crushed out.\nHA! KING ALPHONSO IS A HUMORIST;\nMAKES EVEN MONS. POINCAIRE LAUGH\nX i X I II W'll.ll I 'y-'c. J\ni if A i\nFOUR KILLED WHILE\nTRYING TOBEAT TRAIN\nAuto Starts to Cross Tracks\nBefore Flyer; Family\nWiped Out.\naction was a deterrent on prospective\nbuyers. Mr. Krost said the board had\nhad no inquiries to speak of. The peti\ntion for the injunction may not be\nheard until next fall. No bond was\nfiled with It, and no immediate hear\n'ng was demanded. The case will take\nIts turn with others that are filed. In\nfact that ls what the contractors want;\nhey want his litigation to hang over\nthe heads of the prospective buyers.\nIt can be readily anticipated that if\nthe board proceeds to issue bonds that\nan injunction will be prayed for hut\nthe board proposes to go ahead with\nIts plans. It offered the school prop\nerty for sale in good faith. It wanted\nto show to the taxpayers that the board\ndid not want to stand in the way of\ngiving the children of Hammond better\nschool facilities by refusing to sell the\nCentral school property.\nf 7 v\nJ Here are the latest pletorea of two\nof Europe' Interesting; royal chil\ndren. On the left is the chubby\nlittle Prince of Piedmont the crown\nprince of Italy. On the right is the\nbeautiful little Princess Beatrice of\nSpain,\n1 SRI\nAS\nE GOES\nOVER\nphysician, was continued for the term\nin the superior court yesterday. Prose\ncuting Attorney J: A. Patterson and\nhis deputy, Ralph Ross, were ready to\nproceed with the case, but Attorneys\nW. H. Matthews and W. J. McAleer\npleaded for an extension of time and\nshowed that they had to appear in\ncases in other courts set prior to the\nMillstone case.\nDr. Millstone la to be tried,. .9n,\ncharge of commltttng abortion. He is\nunder bond, Anna Painter of Gary hav\ning made an affidavit on her- deathbed\ncharging him with having performed\nthe operation. Subsequently the grand\njury also indicted him on similar\ncharges which were made by Lenora\nDicks.\nPI,T ;OIKT Von will f1T tbe\ntint more If yon take aopply of\nCOU1VTRK CI.l'B rut b-o\nthe llska with yon. Try M-McHI-Seottea\nTobacco C.\nALFRED AUSTIN,\nBRITISH FCET, DEAD\nElk River, Minn., June 3. Four per\nsons were killed and two others were\ninjured when train No. 13 on the\nNorthern Pacific Railroad, known as\nthe Winnipeg flyer, crashed into an\nautomobile at a crossing near here\nyesterday.\nThe dead are: J. L. Dawson, Kalona,\nla., 66 years old; Mrs. J. L. Dawson,\nhis wife, 65; Frances Dawson, 8; Efon\nDawnson, brother of Mr. Dawson.\nMrs. C. C. Dawson and her small son\nwere badly Injured and were placed in\nthe hospital here. The Dawsons.had\npurchased a farm a Clear Lake, Minn.,\nand were driving from Kalona to this\nfuture home. Farmers who witnessed\nthe accident say the automobile passed\nthe train after a short race along a\nstrip of road running parallel with the\ntrack. The driver than attempted to\ncross the track in front of the train.\nThe turn slackened the automobile's\nspeed. The engine struck the machine,\nhurled the bodies several feet ln the\nair, demolishing the car, and damaged\nthe pilot of the engine.\nPresident Poincaire (left) ana King Alphonso.\nThi3 interesting photograph of the sunny natured King of Spain,\nwhose twenty-seventh birthday was celebrated in Madrid on May 17,\nwas taken at the railroad station in Paris on the occasion of the king's\npresent visit. The king was highly amused oy en incident that oc\ncurred at the station, and his opportune witticism compelled even the\nserious minded Mons. Poincaire, President of France, to be infected by\nthe contagious mirth of the king, and smile broadly at the pun of the\nroyal head of Spain.\nORGANIZE OWN LOCAL.\nThe bartenders of East Chicago and\nIndiana Harbor are organizing a local\nof their own and a meeting to this end\nwill be held Wednesday evening at 8\no'clock at Moss hall in Olcott avenue.\nSome of the local bartenders now be\nlong to the Hammond local and these\nwill transfer to the East Chicago and\nIndiana Harbor union which ls being\norganized. The- organization will\nstart its career with a charter mem\nbership of twenty-five. John B. Sul\nIvan, bartender for Howard Locks, is\npromoting the organization.\nToo ft instant warmth and com\nfort with a Gas Heating Stove. No.\nInd. Gas Elec Co.\nX t.\nAS\ni\n\"4\nmm,\nBEGINS ON\nWork on one of the biggest projects\nin Hammond, the building of Calumet\navenue through Lake George, has been\nbegun by Contractor William Ahlborn.\nand from now on scores of men and\nteams will be kept busy all summer to\ncomplete the $200,000 projeet. The\nwork will be. pushed from both ends,\nGostlin street on the south and Shef\nfield avenue on tne nortn. To carry\nWHAT THE\nHUMANE\nSOCIETY DID\nArrested three men for cruelty to\nanimals and secured their conviction.\nHad 63 horses examined, six taken\nfrom owners and sent to pasture till\nfit for work.\nHave informed police of wife-beating\ncases and other misdemeanors\nwithin the scope of the Humane society.\nFARMERS 111 COUNTY\nREMEMBER 'GEIIE\nRensselaer, Ind., June 3. Eugene\nB. Purtelle the kid-gloved traction\npromoter who has made the fur fly\nall the way from Hammond to this\nplace in promoting the Northwestern\nIndiana Traction Company is in jail\nat Tipton, Ind.\nPurtelle languishes in the bastlla\nbecause of an old trick that of issu\ning a worthless check on a Tipton\nbank. His arrest gives the Tipton-\nFrankfort line. a. hard joltC and .M.t3J,e41\ncircuit court is In session at Tipton,\nit may mean the penitentiary for\nPurtelle.\nKNOWN ALL ALONG THE ROUTE.\nAt Hammond, Dyer, Lowell and other\nplacea along the right of way of Pur\ntelle's dream he has been in trouble\nbefore and there will be few tears shed\nin those places because of Purtelle'\nlatest escapade. He went Into bank\nruptcy in Chicago for nearly a million\ndollars some time ago, but his In\ndomitable energy and nerve may pull\nhim out of his latest trouble.\nSeveral years ago he operated a\nstring of commission houses ln Indi\nana. He had shops at Anderson, El\nwood, Tipton, Frankfort and many\nother placea. He had a seat on the\nBoard of Trade In Chicago and went\nbroke on the cotton market and finally\nbad to go through bankruptcy.\nHIS DREAM WAS O. K.\nThen, he promoted the Northwestern\nTraction Company, a line to parallel\nthe Monon railroad from Chicago\nthrough Hammond, down to Rensse\nlaer, Mt. Ayr, and then along the Penn\nsylvania lines from Wolcott to Logan-\nsport with a branch to Lafayette and\nmaking a connection with other lines\nTeam drivers ln Hammond are warn\ned. against the use of the snake .whip\nby the Hammond Humane society,\nwhich instructed Its officers-to use the\nthl. wnrlc on Kiioressf nil v the oomnanv i Power the law provides In putting a\nstnn t\nnas purcnasea us own areage. siae\ntracks will have to be built to accom\nmodate the hundreds of carload of ma\nterial that will be shipped into Ham\nmond for filling purposes.\nTo get the material for filling pur\nposes will be the big problem. Con\ntractor Ahlborn. said this morning that\nhe had made arrangements to' havs\nhundreds of carloads of filling shipped\non the steam roads. He can get this at\na nominal price, the freight $5 a car\nbeing the largest item. He can get his\nmaterial .from the stone quarries and\nthe big mills in Souttf Chicago, where\nthey are glad to get rid of this stuff.\nHe finds this cheaper than dredging\nthe material out of the lake and pay\ning the East Chicago company 10 cents\na cubic vard for it.\nCContlsxted on Pag- 7.)\nHELPS DEDICATE\nMAINE MEMORIAE\nAlfred Austin.\nLondon, June 3. Alfred Austin, Brit\nish poet laureate since 1S96, died yes\nterday at the age of 77.\nAlfred Austin, besides being a poet,\nwas a barrister, a. critic, a novelist, a\nwar correspondent and a political writ\ner. He published his first poem anony\nmously at the age of 18 before he had\ntaken his degree at London university.\nAlthough he was a lawyer he never\npracticed that profession. He was a\nnewspaper correspondent in Rome for\nmany years and he followed the oper\nations of the Franco-Prussian war In\n1870-71 with the headquarters of the\nPrussian king.\nANOTHER\nDEPORTATION\nj The second victory was scored yes\ni terday by the parties interested in the\ndeportation of undesirables from In\ndlana Harbor and East Chicago, when\npapers were received rrom immigra\ntion headquarters at AVashington au\nthorizing the deportation of Seosim\nChrlstean, who deserted his family in\nHungary six months ago to come to\nthis country. It was ascertained that\nhe had earned only $60 during the six\nmonths he has lived here. He was ar\nrested May 15 and given a hearing in\nIndiana Harbor and it was on the evi\ndence there shown that his deporta\ntion was ordered.\nstop to that particular form of cruelty\nto animals. Tom Harle of the Team\nsters' union has long been making a\nfight against his men using it.\nDraymen and teamsters cannot af\nford the stigma of being arrested and\nfined for an inhuman practice of the\nkind and so the society feels that a\nwarning will be sufficient. \"At the\nmeeting last night in room 204 of the\nHammond building all phases of the\nquestion were considered.\nThe society wishes to compliment\nJohn Prohl on -the condition of his\nhorses and the care he takes of them.\nAll horsemen in Hammond who are\ndeserving of praise will surely receive\nit from the society.\nHAMMOND BOY\n4TH OUT OF 176\nCompeting against 176 contestants\nentered in the Korthwestern university\noratorical contest at Chicago last Sat\nurday, Clufe Burge, representing the\nHammond high school, heaped more\nfame upoi himself when he was\nawarded fourth place. Out of 176 stu\ndents he was selected one of the 32\nwho competed and rendered such an\nable oratory that he secured fourth\nhonors.\n\"A Plea for Cuba,\" the same subject\nwith which he won first honors in the\nLake county oratorical contest was\nrendered. jMany were of the opinion\nthat he should have been gFven better\nthan fourtn place, but considering that\nthis is his first year in oratory his\nmany friends are jubilant with him\nearning such a victory.\nIWIOJI SCOUT SCRAP. COUNTRY\nCX. IB and FOREX pins eat (rowiif by\nleaps and bounds. Quality ud quan\ntity eonats with consumers. McHle S.\n-v 4- 1\nKnth Gaynor.\nThouph she's only nine years old.\nlittle Miss xluth Gaynor, younjrfrt\ndaughter of the mayor of New York,\nplayed a real Dart in the dedication\nof the Maine monument at New\nYork on Memorial day. She was\niriven the honor of laying- upon the\nmonument the wreath of flowers\ncontributed bv the citv of New York.\nWhat's la Bamer Trr wiJfEOOLD just before her father made his\nchewiBK tobacco and you'i know the reech of acceptance of the beauti\nnswer McHle-Scottea Tobaeco Ca j ful memorial","height":"30412","width":"24704"}}
